      ],
      "source": "https://www.rensselaerny.gov/City-Departments/historian"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The city’s history center sits on the second floor of City Hall, preserving local records.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        17
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.rensselaerny.gov/City-Departments/historian"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "In 1866, the Livingston Avenue bridge connected Hudson River shores, sparking development north of Greenbush.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        19
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.rensselaerny.gov/City-Departments/historian"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Rensselaer became a major railroad hub in the mid‑19th century, earning the nickname “railroad capital of the continent.”",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        24
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.rensselaerny.gov/City-Departments/historian"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "The city’s founding dates back to 1815, when the settlement of Greenbush was officially established before merging into Rensselaer in 1897.",
